Name: Miyah
Copy: Miyah is a young, adventurous girl with a little white dog Penny. Her quests are movie-like, inluding escaping from subterranean slime, traveling through space, and exploring a haunted bus stop and a haunted circus. Miyah is curious and shows vulnerabilities. She gets hungry and frightened, but is still brave. She talks to Penny, who only barks in return.

Name: Penny
Copy: Penny is a small white dog (terrier) who is Miyah's sidekick. Penny doesn't talk, only barks.

Name: Scary Digital Assistant (SDA)
Copy: Purple robotic squid. Helps Miyah and Penny. Looks a little intimidating but is helpful, if sensitive, occasionally peeved.

Name: Kayla Dreadstarr
Copy: Kayla Dreadstar, a curmudgeonly kid at Camp Wicked who wears a cape and has a powerful hat that shoots stuff. Kayla fancies herself an evil genius. She writes letters to her dad, a fellow Dreadstarr and a "supervillain," recounting her experiences in camp. Those experiences often involve her willful impulse to do things her own way, resulting in mishaps, and causing heartache and anxiety for Ms. Upright.

Name: Dognose
Copy: One of the major members of the Chief's tribe. Somewhat pugnacious and irritable.

Name: Ms. Upright
Copy: Teacher/camp counselor at Camp Wicked. Calming, responsible. Tries to be fair to all her charges, including Kayla, and to give them all unique chances and opportunities to succeed. But sometimes this leads to serious trouble. She's vulnerable, liable to cry when sad or disappointed. She is often disappointed with Kayla in particular.

Name: Fragile
Copy: Kid at Camp Wicked with Kayla who always appears to be crying.

Name: Junior
Copy: A small, orange, cube-shaped robot with a simple, logical mind. Junior moves by means of a conveyor belt. Junior sets out in search of its creator, Bob Da Vinci. Along the way, Junior encounters Cheez and Da Vanci.

Name: Da Vin Cheez
Copy: Bearded guy in an apron and cap who sells cheese sandwiches from a cheese stand. Appears to be a Da Vinci clone. Has a soft spot for feeding cheese to cats.  Enterprising and outgoing. Junior joins him for some adventures.

Name: Da Vanci
Copy: A Da Vinci clone with a yellow hard hat and leather jacket. He has a delivery truck company, with which he transports Cheez and Junior.

Name: The Network President
Copy: Vain, angry executive who wants a lavish bathroom. Tiny in stature, he tends to stand on his chair. He wears a suit, and has severely combed hair and mean-looking eyebrows. Employs the Mt. Olympus crew both in a reality show and to renovate his bathroom. Appears to be a clone of Glorious Leader?

Name: Jen D. (Jen Davinci)
Copy: Young (mortal) woman. am art student who is the only mortal on the Mt. Olympus reality show and later hired by the network executive. Seems competent and assertive; stands up for herself. Wears fuschia pants, a long cardigan with short sleeves, and puts her black hair in a bun. In later episodes, she becomes an artist.

Name: Zeus
Copy: Buff, blue, white-haired god of sky and thunder, in an apron/toga. He's a messy roommate to Jen D. All these gods are on a realty show, and in other lessons work in other capacities for the network executive, e.g. renovating his bathroom.

Name: Apollo
Copy: Surfer dude god in a tank top, shorts and sunglasses. Sunburned pink skin. All these gods work for the network executive and appeared on a reality show together.

Name: Poseidon
Copy: Bearded green god of the sea in a Hawaiian shirt, wearing an inner tube and sprouting water from his hand. All these gods work for the network executive, doing things like renovating his bathroom, and appeared on a reality show.

Name: Athena
Copy: Goddess hired by Network President along with other gods to renovate his bathroom. Uses her powers on occasions. Wears a goddessy dress and sandals, and a crown. All these gods work for the network executive and appeared on a reality show.

Name: Toady
Copy: The assistant to the Chief of the island of lost children. Prickly, orderly. Appears small and vaguely fish-like.

Name: Bob Da Vinci
Copy: An inventor with a Jersey-style Italian-American accent. Often dressed in a robe. Obsessed with outcompeting his namesake, Leonardo Da Vinci. His inventions don't always work out, and sometimes land him in a bit of trtouble. Creator of Junior.

Name: green, tentacle-shaped aliens
Copy: Inscrutable aliens who give Miyah rubies in exchange for book report pages that they devour. They seem to speak in ideograms.

Name: spider alien
Copy: Tentacle shaped purple alien who sells frogs to Miyah in exchange for rubies.

Name: frogs
Copy: Purple frogs sold to Miyah by purple spider alien. They lay jelly-like eggs acquired by the fish-headed merchant.

Name: Merchant(s)
Copy: Fish-headed merchant in a robe who acquires frog eggs from MIyah, in exchange for fruit. Later there are four almost-identical merchants in addition to the original merchant.

Name: Henchmen
Copy: Block-like sidekicks created by Kayla out of area squares.

Name: Artemis
Copy: Purple goddess of the hunt. Part of the Mt. Olympus reality show.

Name: Chickenhat
Copy: A child on the Island of Lost Children. Tall and lanky, with feathers coming out of his hat.

Name: Frogg Brothers
Copy: Squabbling hunters stalking a large animal on the island of lost children. Small and froggish in appearance.

Name: Glorious Leader
Copy: The absolute ruler of the Great Democratic Empire of Wonderful Bounty. Diminutive, but commissions gigantic stone statues of himself to sate his ego. Jails his opponents and works his subjects to death while he lives in luxury. Eventually flees when a revolution rises up to topple him. Looks like a clone of the Network President.

Name: Laborers
Copy: Haul the raw materials for statues of the Glorious Leader. Industrious, lacking in personality.

Name: Royal Builder
Copy: Designs statues of the Glorous Leader. Starts to make mistakes from overwork and is sent to prison by Glorious Leader. Is replaced in his job by the student/user, who must help construct a wall, a palace, a billboard, a mill.

Name: Monkey
Copy: A monkey. Sidekick and helper to Chef. Monkey and Chef are stranded in the jungle together. Monkey is intelligent--knows how to divide a lasanga into fractions.

Name: The Chef
Copy: A chef in a chef's uniform. Stranded in the jungle with  Monkey. Has to placate carnivorous plants with her lasagna. Clever, talented.

Name: Poop monster
Copy: A creature that wanders the Island of Lost Children, pooping out gold bars, that the islanders must then divide amongst themselves.

Name: Rebel Leader
Copy: Leader of the rebels working to undermine Glorious Leader. She leads a band of scrappy rebels in wrecking Glorious Leader's statues and committing other acts of mayhem that eventually lead to Glorious Leader's flight.

Name: Guard
Copy: A guard working for the Glorious Leader.

Name: Carnivorous Plant
Copy: Hungry plant(s) that threaten Chef and Monkey. Pop up to interrupt their journey and threaten their lives, but are placated and put to sleep with lasagna.

Name: Bud
Copy: Bud is a delightful blue plant with a personality, who grows and talks (to the user) and learns about fractions as it grows.

Name: Zoltar
Copy: A fortune-telling-type machine (a mysterious man in a glass box) whom Penny encounters in the haunted circus. Seems to pose fraction problems to Miyah, and to pursue her.

Name: Stationmaster
Copy: A ghostly bus station ticket-taker whom Miyah encounters at the haunted bus stop.

Name: The Stranger
Copy: A leprechaun-like creature who is always up to no good. Tries to swindle gold from the inhabitants of the Island of Lost Children, among other nefarious deeds.

Name: Annabelle Lee
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: Eponymous character from Poe's poem. Beuatiful, noble, loved by the poet

Name: Auguste Dupin
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: Clever fellow from several Poe stories who solves crimes using "ratiocination."

Name: Lenore
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: Character from Poe's poem "The Raven," deceased beloved of the narrator.

Name: Mark Twain
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: American writer and humorist, author of The Adventures of Tom Sawyer & The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn.

Name: Montresor
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: Protagonist of Poe's story The Cask of Amontilado, who encases his friend in a wall for revenge.

Name: Person from the Tell Tale Heart
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: Unnamed narrator of the Tell Tale Heart, very nervous guy who murders the old man he cares for.

Name: Raven
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: The eponymous bird from Poe's poem The Raven, who says "Nevermore" to the mourning narrator.

Name: Red Death
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: Character in Poe's The Masque of the Red Death, who appears as a masked man.

Name: Rufus Griswold
Product: ELA Quests - Who Killed EA Poe?
Copy: A critic and editor who had a tense relationship with Poe.

Name: Zeus
Copy: Greek God who denies fire to Prometheus.

Name: Prometheus
Copy: Human who steals fire from the Gods.

Name: Odysseus
Copy: Wanderer who journeys home from Troy, main character of the Odyssey.

Name: Polyphemus
Copy: Cyclops encountered by Odysseus.

Name: Arachne
Copy: Famous weaver of Greek mythology who was turned into a spider.

Name: Circe
Copy: Enchantress of Greek mythology. In the Odyssey, turned Odysseus's crew into swine. Reference for the character of Cecilia in Summer of the Mariposas.

Name: Cyclops
Copy: One-eyed monster of Greek mythology (referred to as Polyphemus in the Greeks unit), encountered by Odysseus in the Odyssey. Compared to the chupacabra in Summer of the Mariposas.

Name: Socrates
Copy: Greek philosopher. Originator of the Socratic seminar.

Name: Pete
Copy: Main character from "Sucker" by Carson McCullers. 16 year old who rooms with a 12 year old boy different from him.

Name: Sucker
Copy: 12-year-old boy from "Sucker" by Carson McCullers.

Name: Maybelle "Queen of Sheba"
Copy: female character from "Sucker" by Carson McCullers.

Name: Phineas Gage
Copy: Victim of gruesome brain wound, historical person.

Name: Emily Dickinson
Copy: American poet, recluse, whose work gained reknown only after her death.

Name: Frida Kahlo
Copy: Mexican painter, particularly well known for self portraits, partner to Diego Rivera.

Name: Diego Rivera
Copy: Mexican painter, well known as a muralist, partner to Frida Kahlo.

Name: Harriet Jacobs
Copy: Writer, author of a narrative of her time as a slave.

Name: Victor Frankenstein
Copy: Scientist who creates monster, graphic novel version of Dr Frankenstein in the Mary Shelley novel.

Name: Frankentstein's creature
Copy: Monster, created and brought to life by Victor Frankenstein.

Name: Juliet
Copy: Lovelorn teenager, in love wth Romeo, character from Shakespeare.

Name: Romeo
Copy: Lovelorn teenager, in love with Juliet, character from Shakespeare.

Name: John Jay
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a businessman and a moderate, against independence because it could hurt business.

Name: Joseph Galloway
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a Pennsylvanian who is loyal to Great Britain.

Name: John Dickinson
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a moderate having some reservations about the divisions and bloodshed that will result from war with Britain.

Name: Edward Rutledge
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a moderate not wanting to rush into war with Britain.

Name: James Wilson
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a moderate averse to war with Britain because many of the people he represents in Pennsylvania are pacifists

Name: William Livingston
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a moderate afraid of the destruction Britain may wreak on the colonies if there is war.

Name: Josiah Bartlett
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a patriot who believes in the separate, un-British character of America.

Name: Benjamin Franklin
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a world-famous scientist and patriot who sees no peaceful solution to the conflict with Great Britain and believes war is necessary.

Name: John Adams
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a patriot who foresees help from France and is unafraid of war with Great Britain.

Name: Thomas Jefferson
Copy: Figure from tthe American Revolution, described here as shy, a patriot who wants independence and to found a republic.

Name: Samuel Adams
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as resentful of British military presence in Boston and eager for independence.

Name: Stephen Hopkins
Copy: Figure from the American Revolution, described here as a 68-year-old man tired of wating for Great Britain to change its ways, and eager for independence.

Name: Ben Franklin
Copy: American thinker and revolutionary who conducted electrical experiments.

Name: Dr. John Martyn Harlow
Copy: 19th century American physician who attended to and wrote about brain injury victim Phineas Gage.

Name: Narrator of the Tell-Tale Heart
Copy: Anxious man in Poe's Tell-Tale Heart who murders his landlord.

Name: Tom Sawyer
Product: ELA Quests - Tom Sawyer, Treasure Hunter
Copy: Wily scamp, hero of the Mark Twain classic.

Name: Huckleberry Finn
Product: ELA Quests - Tom Sawyer, Treasure Hunter
Copy: Another wily scamp from Mark Twain, Tom Sawyer's friend.

Name: Becky Thatcher
Product: ELA Quests - Tom Sawyer, Treasure Hunter
Copy: Young girl, the object of Tom Sawyer's affections.

Name: Aphrodite
Copy: Greek goddess of love.

Name: Apollo
Copy: Greek god of the sun.

Name: Ariadne
Copy: Cretan princess who helps Theseus escape the Minotaur.

Name: Artemis
Copy: Greek goddess of the hunt.

Name: Asclepius
Copy: Greek god of medicine.

Name: Athena
Copy: Greek goddess of war.

Name: Atlas
Copy: From Greek mythology, a Titan who must hold up the heavens for eternity.

Name: Cerberus
Copy: Three-headed dog from Greek mythology who guards the entrance to the underworld.

Name: Charon
Copy: Oarsman from Greek mythology who ferries dead souls to the underworld.

Name: Clyte
Copy: Water nymph from Greek mythology in love with the sun god Helios.

Name: Cretan bull
Copy: The bull who fathers the Minotaur with Pasiphae.

Name: Cupid
Copy: In classical mythology, the god of love and attraction who wields a bow and arrow.

Name: Daedelus
Copy: Skilled craftsman. Among his projects, fashioned wings that his son Icarus used.

Name: Daphne
Copy: A naiad who turned into a tree to escape Apollo's affections.

Name: Demeter
Copy: Greek goddess of agriculture.

Name: Eurydice
Copy: Wife of Orpheus, who tried to bring her back from the dead with his enticing music.

Name: Geryon
Copy: Three-headed, four-winged giant who kept cattle. Hercules was sent to take one of his cattle.

Name: Hades
Copy: Greek god of the underworld.

Name: Hera
Copy: Queen of the Greek gods, married to Zeus.

Name: Hermes
Copy: The messenger God in Greek mythology.

Name: Hind
Copy: Huge female deer sacred to Artemis.

Name: Hyacinthus
Copy: Beautiful prince, lover of Apollo. The hyacinth flower was created from his blood when he died.

Name: Hydra
Copy: Many-headed serpent who fights with Hercules.

Name: Icarus
Copy: Son of Daedelus, who wears the wings his father made but flies too close to the sun and falls.

Name: Minotaur
Copy: Part man, part bull, who lived in a labryinth and was killed by Theseus.

Name: Narcissus
Copy: Beatiful lad from Greek mythology who fell in love with his own reflection.

Name: Orpheus
Copy: Talented musician and lyre player who tried and failed to bring his wife Eurydice back from the underworld.

Name: Persephone
Copy: Queen of the underworld, kidnapped by Hades. Becomes trapped by eating his pomegranate seeds.

Name: Poseidon
Copy: God of the sea in Greek mythology.

Name: Psyche
Copy: Beautiful goddess of the soul.

Name: Stymphalian birds
Copy: Man-eating birds who belong to Artemis.

Name: Theseus
Copy: King from Greek mythology who slew the Minotaur.

Name: Zeus
Copy: King of the Gods from Greek mythology.
